d man’ (compare   Bald   3).","French: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Balhard</i>, composed of the elements <i>bal</i>, presumably meaning ‘torment, spitefulness’, and <i>hard</i> ‘hard, strong’. Compare   Ballor  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ballon","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Sergio, Alfonso, Cesar, Conchita, Emigdio, Enrique, Felipe, Francisco, Jose Luis, Julio, Ruben.  Jewish Hyman, Isadore.","Spanish and Galician: unexplained.","French and English (Middlesex): from the Old French personal name <i>Ballon</i>, <i>Ballun</i>, derived from the oblique stem of ancient Germanic <i>Ballo</i>, a short form of compound names based on the element <i>bal</i>, presumably meaning ‘torment, spitefulness’ (see   Ballard  )."]},{"name":"Bald","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Inge, Karl-Heinz, Konrad, Kurt, Otto.","German: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Baldo</i>, or a short form of various compound names such as   Baldwin  , formed with the first element <i>bald</i> ‘bold, strong’.","Scottish and English: from the Norman personal name <i>Bald(e)</i>, <i>Baud(e)</i>, occasionally <i>Bold</i>, a short form of the common ancient Germanic personal names   Baldwin   or <i>Baldric</i>, or possibly a survival of Old English <i>Beald</i> (compare   Balding  ); the relevant element in each of these is <i>b(e)ald</i> ‘brave’. As a hereditary surname it seems to have died out in England but survives in Scotland."]},{"name":"Ballor","meanings":["Altered form of French   Ballard   2, reflecting the characteristic Canadian and American French rounding of the <i>-ard</i> ending. It is found mainly in MI."]},{"name":"Bollard","meanings":["English (Northamptonshire) and Irish: probably a variant of   Ballard  . According to MacLysaght, this is a surname of Dutch origin which was taken to Ireland early in the 18th century.","French: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Bolohard</i>, composed of the elements <i>bolo</i> ‘friend, brother’ and <i>hard</i> ‘hard, strong’."]}]},{"name":"Joanna","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form, <i>Io(h)anna</i>, of Greek <i>Iōanna</i>, the feminine equivalent of <i>Iōannēs</i> (  see  John  ). In the New Testament, this name is borne by a woman who was one of Jesus's followers (Luke 8:3; 24:10). She was the wife of the steward of the household of King Herod Antipas. The name was regularly used throughout the Middle Ages in most parts of Europe as a feminine equivalent of   John  , but in England it has only been in common use as a vernacular given name since the 19th century. Celebrated British bearers of the name include the novelist  Joanna Trollope  (  b. 1943 ), the actress  Joanna Lumley  (  b. 1946 ), and the concert pianist  Joanna McGregor  (  b. 1959 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Joannah","meanings":["From the Latin form, <i>Io(h)anna</i>, of Greek <i>Iōanna</i>, the feminine equivalent of <i>Iōannēs</i> (  see  John  ). In the New Testament, this name is borne by a woman who was one of Jesus's followers (Luke 8:3; 24:10). She was the wife of the steward of the household of King Herod Antipas. The name was regularly used throughout the Middle Ages in most parts of Europe as a feminine equivalent of   John  , but in England it has only been in common use as a vernacular given name since the 19th century. Celebrated British bearers of the name include the novelist  Joanna Trollope  (  b. 1943 ), the actress  Joanna Lumley  (  b. 1946 ), and the concert pianist  Joanna McGregor  (  b. 1959 )."]},{"name":"Joana","meanings":["From the Latin form, <i>Io(h)anna</i>, of Greek <i>Iōanna</i>, the feminine equivalent of <i>Iōannēs</i> (  see  John  ). In the New Testament, this name is borne by a woman who was one of Jesus's followers (Luke 8:3; 24:10). She was the wife of the steward of the household of King Herod Antipas. The name was regularly used throughout the Middle Ages in most parts of Europe as a feminine equivalent of   John  , but in England it has only been in common use as a vernacular given name since the 19th century. Celebrated British bearers of the name include the novelist  Joanna Trollope  (  b. 1943 ), the actress  Joanna Lumley  (  b. 1946 ), and the concert pianist  Joanna McGregor  (  b. 1959 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":5,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":40,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":71,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Joanna Ballard was born on 18 December 1218, in Colemore, Hampshire, England. She had at least 2 sons with William Ballard. She died in 1292, in Hampshire, England, at the age of 74."},"et":{"18 December 1218–1292":"18. detsember 1218–1292","1192–Male":"1192–Surnud","1245–1325":"1245–1325","1250–1346":"1250–1346","1218–1292":"1218–1292","ABT 1250":"umbes 1250","1259":"1259","1325":"1325","1346":"1346","1224":"1224","1245":"1245","18 December 1218":"18. detsember 1218","1250":"1250","1292":"1292","1192":"1192","1290":"1290","1218":"1218","Colmer, Hampshire, England":"Colemore, Hampshire, England","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hamp